ines some of the most pressing questions raised by genetic engineering. What determines whether GEOs enter the food supply, and how are such decisions being made? How is the biotechnology industry using its power to reshape food, fiber, and pharmaceutical production, and how are citizen-activists challenging these initiatives? And what are the social and political consequences of global differences over GEOs?  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgricultural biotechnologyxSocial aspects. 0aFoodxBiotechnologyxSocial aspects. 0aGenetic engineeringxSocial aspects. 4aEnvironmental Conservation & Protection. 4aNature. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aBoyd, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButtel, Frederick H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoyle, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodman, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuthman, Julie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelso, Dennis Takahashi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKelso, Takahashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAfee, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMunro, William A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrudham, W. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScholz, Astrid J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchurman, Rachel A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchurman, Rachel A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part 